<subSubSection pageId="306" pageNumber="307" type="diversity">
<paragraph pageId="306" pageNumber="307">Diversity.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="306" pageNumber="307">
About 290 species (
<normalizedToken originalValue="Häckel">Haeckel</normalizedToken>
et al. 2010) in the Nearctic (four species, one of them adventive), Neotropical (about 30 species, one in Mexico, the other ones in South America), Australian (about 180 species), Oriental (five species), and Palaearctic (about 70 species) Regions placed in 34 genera. The genera are arrayed in five subtribes (
<normalizedToken originalValue="Roig-Juñent">Roig-Junent</normalizedToken>
2000): 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hope" authorityYear="1838" genus="Broscina" lsidName="" pageId="306" pageNumber="307" rank="genus">Broscina</taxonomicName>
(about 75 species), 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jeannel" authorityYear="1941" genus="Creobiina" lsidName="" pageId="306" pageNumber="307" rank="genus">Creobiina</taxonomicName>
(about 95 species in South America and the Australian Region), 
<taxonomicName genus="Anoxyina" lsidName="" pageId="306" pageNumber="307" rank="genus">Anoxyina</taxonomicName>
(five species in Mexico, Iran, and the Oriental Region), 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jeannel" authorityYear="1941" genus="Baripodina" lsidName="" pageId="306" pageNumber="307" rank="genus">Baripodina</taxonomicName>
(about 25 South American species), and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Roig-Junent" authorityYear="2000" genus="Nothobroscina" lsidName="" pageId="306" pageNumber="307" rank="genus">Nothobroscina</taxonomicName>
(about 90 species in the Australian Region and one in Chile). The group is better represented in the New World with about 215 species (74% of the world fauna) than in the Old World.
</paragraph>
